<br>
The Great Underground Empire and all that.<br>
<br>
That was back when 128k of memory in a computer was<br>
pretty good.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
(The book &quot;the Zork Chronicles&quot; is fun for those who ever<br>
played the trilogy.  It's set largely in the GUE.)<br>
<br>
Until I got my connections online all set up, I used to play<br>
a lot of the gaming platform &quot;RPG&quot;s.  (I put that in quotes<br>
because no computer or computer-type game can possibly<br>
account for all the things that can happen in an RPG.)<br>
The Final Fantasy series was always a lot of fun.<br>
I played FF II and III (US versions), and only bought a <br>
Playstation when it was announced FF VII was coming.<br>
I was also one of the people who liked 8.  I've played some<br>
of the others on the SNES and Playstation, also. <br>
<br>
I used to play the tabletop RPGs when I could find other<br>
players.  I ran AD &amp; D in my neighborhood, talked another<br>
guy into running the Star Wars RPG for variety (he had fun,<br>
too), and tried to get someone else to run Toon (the<br>
slapstick cartoon game).  That was before White Wolf's<br>
games pretty much took over (Vampire, Werewolf, et al).<br>
I DID play the Live Action Role Playing (LARP) versions of<br>
Werewolf when I could find the things in NYC.  <br>
(I've given up on attempts to run my own LARP.)<br>
That was a LOT of fun, and my best excuse to dress up.<br>
(My spiffiest photos are from when I played well-dressed<br>
characters.)<br>
<br>
I'm currently avoiding games like &quot;Everquest&quot; because I don't<br>
like the idea of work and sleep interrupting my gaming instead<br>
of the other way around. <br>
<br>
My favourite board game-when I can find people to play it-<br>
is the Star Trek vcr board game.  It's a boardgame where<br>
events onscreen affect what's going on during the game.<br>
(It's also funny to watch even if you don't play.)<br>
=========================================<br>
Peaches, there are many types of games CALLED RPGs.<br>
The oldest type is referred to as &quot;tabletop&quot; RPGs<br>
(RolePlaying Games).  Those involve pencils, paper and<br>
funny-shaped dice.   The most popular ones have included<br>
Dungeons &amp; Dragons (or Advanced D &amp; D), and the<br>
WhiteWolf games (mentioned above).<br>
Playing is by description.  Dice are rolled and compared to<br>
various charts to determine success or failure of various<br>
tasks. (The higher your skill, the more dice, or lower the<br>
number needed to roll.)  <br>
Live Action (LARP) is based on tabletop, but you act it out<br>
instead of describing it.  It's one part RPG, one part <br>
improvisational theater.  (I find it a LOT of fun.) <br>
The ones on game machines (like Final Fantasy) are not<br>
truly RPGs, but are called that.  They retain certain trappings<br>
of games like D &amp; D (combat, magic, experience gains you<br>
levels, which improve your skills), but without the interaction<br>
and flexibility which makes an RPG as fun as it is.<br>
Online ones like Ultima and EverQuest are based on those,<br>
but allow players to have their characters interact.  <br>
(STILL not as flexible as the &quot;old-school&quot; tabletops.<br>
 When HOW you cross a room can have infinite variety, <br>
 you REALLY have options.)<br>
<br>
<br>
